  <div class="faq-item">
    <h3 class="faq-question">Do we need exclusive use?</h3>
    <p class="faq-answer">Depends on venue and guest count. Properties under 50 rooms often require exclusive use. Larger hotels may offer exclusive use as option rather than requirement. Consider whether having the venue to yourselves matters for your celebration style.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <h3 class="faq-question">What's included in venue pricing?</h3>
    <p class="faq-answer">Varies significantly by venue. <strong>All-inclusive examples:</strong> Borgo Egnazia includes catering, bar, planning services, and accommodation in their packages. <strong>Venue-only examples:</strong> Villa Pizzo charges venue rental separately, with catering, bar, and decor sourced independently. <strong>Hybrid:</strong> Many venues like Villa d'Este include catering and bar but charge separately for planning and decor. Always clarify total costs including service charges, taxes, and required vendors.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <h3 class="faq-question">How do we handle guest accommodation?</h3>
    <p class="faq-answer">For venues with onsite rooms: negotiate room block rates. For event-only venues: arrange accommodation at nearby hotels with shuttle coordination. Multi-day celebrations benefit enormously from everyone staying together onsite.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <h3 class="faq-question">What about legal requirements?</h3>
    <p class="faq-answer">Italy allows both civil and Catholic ceremonies at licensed venues. Requirements include documentation filed 90 days before, but most venues work with coordinators who handle the process. Symbolic ceremonies (not legally binding) face no restrictions and most couples find these easier.</p>
  </div>
